Here is the translation, explanation, and comparative analysis of the passage from *Xunzi*.

### (1) English Translation

Marquis Wu of Wei was planning affairs of state and his decisions were correct; none of his ministers could match his ability. When he retired from the court, he wore a look of joy.

Wu Qi stepped forward and said, "Have you ever heard the words of King Zhuang of Chu spoken in your presence?"

Marquis Wu asked, "What were King Zhuang of Chu's words like?"

Wu Qi replied, "King Zhuang of Chu planned affairs of state and his decisions were correct; none of his ministers could match him. When he retired from the court, he wore a look of worry. Shen Gong Wu臣 stepped forward and asked, 'Why does the King look worried upon leaving the court?'

King Zhuang replied, 'I planned affairs correctly, yet none of my ministers could match me. This is why I am worried. There is a saying in the *Zhonggu**: "A feudal lord who treats others as his teachers will become a true King (Wang); one who treats others as his friends will become a Hegemon (Ba); one who treats others as his subordinates/skeptics will survive; but one who plans alone and finds no one equal to himself will perish." Now, with my lack of virtue, and yet none of my ministers able to match me, is my state not on the verge of destruction! This is why I am worried.'

King Zhuang of Chu felt worry, yet you, My Lord, feel joy."

Marquis Wu stepped back, bowed twice, and said, "It is Heaven that has sent you, Master, to correct my faults."

